reviews.content:
I was lead to review this film by finding its' name on lists of 'Best French Films of The 1960's', 'Top 100 - Sexuality In Film', and 'Top 100 Films Featuring Paris'.I admit that I did not give this film the proper attention on my first viewing, and I found it difficult to follow. Although I take responsibility, I was not knowledgeable of (or, apparently prepared for) 'surrealistic French directing'. There are sudden scene changes to both flashbacks and fantasies - all in the same style, and with no transition effects. If you leave the room to refill your drink, you can ruin the film experience by missing an important 20 second scene with no dialog. Again, this film requires attention - especially if French is not your first language.Films about sexuality should contain great nudity of some sort. This film does not. I do not care for Luis Brunel's directing or writing style. Maybe Catherine Deneuve felt the same, because she should have given more to this role. She was mostly unemotional and stiff, and the character was written in an irrational way.I've seen this a few times now. The location shots in Paris and the French countryside are pretty cool. The story is compelling. This film is good, but it could have been great.RealReview Posting Scoring Criteria:
